<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Picea</i> <i>breweriana</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the tree canopy with <i>Abies</i> <i>concolor</i>, <i>Abies</i> <i>procera</i>, <i>Abies</i> Ã—<i>shastensis</i>, <i>Calocedrus</i> <i>decurrens</i>, <i>Chamaecyparis</i> <i>lawsoniana</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>lambertiana</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>monticola</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>ponderosa</i>, <i>Pseudotsuga</i> <i>menziesii</i>, <i>Taxus</i> <i>brevifolia</i> and <i>Tsuga</i> <i>mertensiana</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text"> Trees < 60 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Shrub layer is sparse to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is sparse or abundant. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Picea breweriana</i> is > 30% relative cover and > 5% absolute cover in the tree layer (NatureServe 2007).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> North slopes and rocky ridges. Parent materials and soils are highly variable.  </div>
</div>

        
